# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chris-von-der-ahe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] After his retirement as a player, Spalding remained active with the Chicago White Stockings as president and part-owner.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In the 1880s, he took players on the first world tour of baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] With William Hulbert, Spalding organized the National League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He later called for the commission that investigated the origins of baseball and falsely credited Abner Doubleday with creating the game.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] As of the 2026 season, Spalding holds the individual records for the fewest career home runs per nine innings (0.0468) and the highest career winning percentage (.794).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Having played baseball throughout his youth, Spalding first played competitively with the Rockford Pioneers, a youth team, which he joined in 1865.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] After pitching his team to a 26–2 victory over a local men's amateur team (the Mercantiles), he was approached at the age of 15 by the Rockford Forest Citys, for whom he played for five years.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] William Hulbert, principal owner of the Chicago White Stockings, did not like the loose organization of the National Association and the gambling element that influenced it, so he decided to create a new organization, which he dubbed the National League of Baseball Clubs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] To aid him in this venture, Hulbert enlisted the help of Spalding.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Playing to the pitcher's desire to return to his Midwestern roots and challenging Spalding's integrity, Hulbert convinced Spalding to sign a contract to play for the White Stockings (now known as the Chicago Cubs) in 1876.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding then coaxed teammates Deacon White, Ross Barnes and Cal McVey, as well as Philadelphia Athletics players Cap Anson and Bob Addy, to sign with Chicago.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] This was all done under complete secrecy during the playing season because players were all free agents in those days and they did not want their current club and especially the fans to know they were leaving to play elsewhere the next year.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] News of the signings by the Boston and Philadelphia players leaked to the press before the season ended and all of them faced verbal abuse and physical threats from the fans of those cities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He was "the premier pitcher of the 1870s", leading the league in victories for each of his six full seasons as a professional.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] During each of those years he was his team's only pitcher.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1876, Spalding won 47 games as the prime pitcher for the White Stockings and led them to win the first-ever National League pennant by a wide margin.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1877, Spalding began to use a glove to protect his catching hand.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] People had used gloves previously, but they were not popular, and Spalding himself was skeptical of wearing one at first.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] However, once he began donning gloves, he influenced other players to do so.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding retired from playing baseball in 1878 at the age of 27, although he continued as president and part owner of the White Stockings and a major influence on the National League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding's .796 career winning percentage (from an era when teams played about once or twice a week) is the highest ever by a baseball pitcher, .058 ahead of Negro league star Dave Brown's .738.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding was the first pitcher to reach 200 wins.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In the months after signing for Chicago, Hulbert and Spalding organized the National League by enlisting the two major teams in the East and the four other top teams in what was then considered to be the West, also known as the jungle.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Joining Chicago initially were the leading teams from Cincinnati, Louisville, and St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The owners of these western clubs accompanied Hulbert and Spalding to New York where they secretly met with owners from New York City, Philadelphia, Hartford, and Boston.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Each signed the league's constitution, and the National League was officially born.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] "Spalding was thus involved in the transformation of baseball from a game of gentlemen athletes into a business and a professional sport." Although the National Association held on for a few more seasons, it was no longer recognized as the premier organization for professional baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Gradually, it faded out of existence and was replaced by myriad minor leagues and associations around the country.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1886, with Spalding as president of the franchise, the Chicago White Stockings (today's Chicago Cubs), began holding spring training in Hot Springs, Arkansas, which subsequently has been called the "birthplace" of spring training baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The location and the training concept was the brainchild of Spalding and his player/manager Cap Anson, who saw that the city and the natural springs created positives for their players.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] They first played in an area called the **Hot Springs Baseball Grounds**.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Many other teams followed the concept and began training in Hot Springs and other locations.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1905, after Henry Chadwick wrote an article saying that baseball grew from the British sports of cricket and rounders, Spalding called for a commission to find out the real source of baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The commission called for citizens who knew anything about the founding of baseball to send in letters.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] After three years of searching, on December 30, 1907, Spalding received a letter that (erroneously) declared baseball to be the invention of Abner Doubleday.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The commission was biased, as Spalding would not appoint anyone to the commission if they believed the sport was somewhat related to rounders or cricket.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Receiving the archives of Henry Chadwick in 1908, Spalding combined these records with his own memories (and biases) to write *America's National Game* (published 1911) which, despite its flaws, was probably the first scholarly account of the history of baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1876 while Spalding was playing and organizing the league, Spalding and his brother Walter began a sporting goods store in Chicago, which grew rapidly (14 stores by 1901) and expanded into a manufacturer and distributor of all kinds of sporting equipment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The company became "synonymous with sporting goods" and is still a going concern.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding, from 1892 to 1941, sold books under the name Spalding Athletic Library on many different sports.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1888–1889, Spalding took a group of major league players around the world to promote baseball and Spalding sporting goods.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] This was the first-ever world baseball tour.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Playing across the western U.S., the tour made stops in Hawaii (although no game was played), New Zealand, Australia, Ceylon, Egypt, Italy, France, and England.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The tour returned to grand receptions in New York, Philadelphia, and Chicago.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The tour included future Hall of Famers Cap Anson and John Montgomery Ward.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The tour was also touted by Spalding as a launching point for baseball to reach the global stage.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] While Spalding and company gushed about their schlep around the world, waxing lyrical about baseball's future as a global sport, in reality, the tour had very little impact on the sport's hold overseas.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Sports like soccer, rugby, and cricket had already been established in many other countries due to the presence of European imperialism so baseball had a difficult time gaining popularity in these regions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] While baseball did reach a wider global audience, it was due to a larger scale diffusion of the sport rather than the efforts of one magnate, like Spalding envisioned.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] While the players were on the tour, the National League instituted new rules regarding player pay that led to a revolt of players, led by Ward, who started the Players' League the following season (1890).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The league lasted one year, partially due to the anti-competitive tactics of Spalding to limit its success.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The tour and formation of the Player's League is depicted in the 2015 movie *Deadball*.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1900 Spalding was appointed by President McKinley as the USA's Commissioner at that year's Summer Olympic Games.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Spalding had been a prominent member of the Theosophical Society under William Quan Judge.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1900, Spalding moved to San Diego having recently married his second wife, Elizabeth and became a prominent member and supporter of the Theosophical community Lomaland, which was being developed on Point Loma by Katherine Tingley.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He built an estate in the Sunset Cliffs area of Point Loma where he lived with Elizabeth for the rest of his life.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The Spaldings raised race horses and collected Chinese fine furniture and art.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] The Spaldings had an extensive library which included many volumes on Theosophy, art, and literature.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] In 1907–1909 he was the driving force behind the development of a paved road, known as the "Point Loma boulevard," from downtown San Diego to Point Loma and Ocean Beach; the road also provided good access to Lomaland.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] It later provided the basis for California State Route 209.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He proposed the project, supervised it on behalf of the city, and paid a portion of the cost out of his own pocket.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He joined with George Marston and other civic-minded businessmen to purchase the site of the original Presidio of San Diego, which they developed as a historic park and eventually donated to the city of San Diego.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He ran unsuccessfully for the United States Senate in 1911 as a Republican, but lost to eventual winner John D.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Works by a vote of 92–21 in the California legislature.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He helped to organize the 1915 Panama–California Exposition, serving as second vice-president.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He died of a stroke on September 9, 1915, in San Diego, one week after his 66th birthday.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] His ashes were scattered at his request.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] He was elected to the Baseball Hall of Fame by the Veterans Committee in 1939, as one of the first inductees from the 19th century at that summer's opening ceremonies.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] His plaque in the Hall of Fame reads "Albert Goodwill Spalding.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Organizational genius of baseball's pioneer days.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] Star pitcher of Forest City Club in late 1860s, 4-year champion Bostons 1871–75 and manager-pitcher of champion Chicagos in National League's first year.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/albert-spalding] His nephew, also named Albert Spalding, was a renowned violinist.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The **American Association of Base Ball Clubs** (**AA**) was a professional baseball league that existed for 10 seasons from 1882 to 1891.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Together with the National League (NL), founded in 1876, the AA participated in an early version of the World Series seven times versus the champion of the NL in an interleague championship playoff tournament.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] At the end of its run, several AA franchises joined the NL.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] After 1891, the NL existed alone, with each season's champions being awarded the Temple Cup (1894–1897).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] During its existence, the AA was often simply referred to as "the Association" in the media, in contrast to the NL, which was sometimes called "the League".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] It was also sometimes called the "Beer and Whiskey League".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The American Association (AA) distinguished itself in several ways from what it considered to be the puritanical National League (NL).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The new league established teams in what the NL leaders pejoratively called "river cities", including Pittsburgh, Cincinnati, Louisville and St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Louis, with the inherent implication of lower morality or social standards in those cities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] In contrast to the NL, the AA offered cheaper ticket prices, Sunday games and alcoholic beverages to its patrons.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] On November 8, 1881, at the Gibson House in Cincinnati, it was decided that individual teams in the league-to-be would operate their own affairs and set their own admission prices, under an agreement called the "guarantee system".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The NL at that time prohibited the sale of alcohol on its grounds, while the AA had no such restrictions, especially as several of its teams were backed by breweries and distilleries.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The AA became known as "The Beer and Whiskey League", another pejorative term applied by NL owners, which did not seem to bother the fans of the Association's clubs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Beginning in 1884 and continuing through 1890, the champion of the AA met the champion of the NL in an early version of the World Series.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] These early Series were less organized than the modern version, with as few as three games played and as many as fifteen, and the contests of 1885 and 1890 ending in disputed ties.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The NL won four of these Series, while the AA won only one, in 1886 when the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Louis Cardinals) defeated the Chicago White Stockings (now the Chicago Cubs).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Over its lifetime, the AA was weakened by several factors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] One was the tendency of some of its teams to jump to the NL.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The consistently stronger NL was in better position to survive adverse conditions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Some owners of AA teams also owned a NL team.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The most significant blow to the AA was dealt by the Players' League, a third major league formed in 1890, which siphoned off talent and gate receipts.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] In a rare historical oddity, the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (now the Los Angeles Dodgers) won the league's championship and represented the AA in the 1889 World Series, switched to the NL during the off-season, and then repeated the same feat.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] No player who spent the majority of his career in the AA is in the baseball Hall of Fame, although Bid McPhee of the Cincinnati Reds played eight of his eighteen seasons in the AA before the Reds moved to the National League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The living legacy of the old Association is the group of teams that came over to the National League to stay.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The Pirates moved to the NL after the 1886 season, the Bridegrooms/Dodgers and the Cincinnati Reds after the 1889 season, and the Browns/Cardinals after the American Association folded following the 1891 season.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Following the reorganization and contraction of the NL from 12 teams down to 8 in 1900, half of the eight surviving teams were former members of the AA.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Several of the AA's home-field venues survived into the 1960s: The ballpark used by the 1891 Washington club evolved into Griffith Stadium; the home of the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns, Sportsman's Park; and the city block occupied by the Reds, which evolved into Crosley Field.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Other than the clubs themselves, Crosley Field was the last physical remnant of the AA—it was the home field of the Cincinnati Reds until mid-season 1970 and was razed in April 1972.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] During the AA's existence, four clubs defected over to the NL: Allegheny City (joined NL 1887, later became the Pittsburgh Pirates), the Cleveland Spiders (joined NL 1889), the Brooklyn Bridegrooms (joined NL 1890, eventually renamed the Dodgers), and the Cincinnati Reds (joined NL 1890).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] At the AA's demise in 1891, four additional clubs joined the NL: the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Louis Browns (later the Cardinals), the Louisville Colonels, the Washington Statesmen (renamed the Senators), and the Baltimore Orioles.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] Therefore, from 1892 to 1899, when the NL consisted of 12 teams, 8 of them had been former AA clubs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] All four have posted more than 10,000 all-time major-league victories.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] AA statistics are recognized by Major League Baseball (MLB), the AA being one of six leagues deemed "major" by the Special Baseball Records Committee of Major League Baseball in 1969.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The first line is the formation of the American Association (AA) in 1882, and the second marks the end of the American Association.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] World's Championship Series championships are shown with a "•", American Association Pennants in non-World Championship Series seasons are shown with a "#", and American Association Pennant winners who tied or lost the World Championship Series are shown with a "^".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] For the 1891 season, the Philadelphia Athletics were replaced by the Philadelphia Quakers of the Player's League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] The 1891 Cincinnati Kelly's Killers folded during the season and were replaced by the Milwaukee Brewers.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-association-19th-century] All non-American Association labels not labeled "NL" (National League) or "PL" (Players' League) are minor league teams.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The **American League of Professional Baseball Clubs**, known simply as the **American League** (**AL**), is the younger of two leagues constituting Major League Baseball (MLB) in the United States and Canada.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] It developed from the Western League, a minor league based in the Great Lakes states, which eventually aspired to major league status.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] It is sometimes called the **Junior Circuit** because it claimed Major League status for the 1901 season, 25 years after the formation of the National League (the "Senior Circuit").
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Since 1903, the American League champion has played in the World Series against the National League champion with only two exceptions: 1904, when the NL champion New York Giants refused to play their AL counterpart, and 1994, when a players' strike resulted in the cancellation of the Series.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Through 2025, American League teams have won 68 of the 121 World Series played since 1903.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The New York Yankees have won 27 World Series and 41 American League titles, the most in major league history.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The Philadelphia/Kansas City/Oakland Athletics have won the second most AL titles with 15, followed by the Boston Red Sox with 14.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] For decades, Major League baseball clubs only played teams from their own league during the regular season and playoffs, with only the two pennant winners meeting in the World Series.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The AL and NL also employed and trained their own umpires, who only worked regular season games in their own league.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] These differences resulted in the leagues developing slightly different strategies and styles of play.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The American League was usually regarded as the less "traditional" league during the 20th century, a reputation most exemplified by the introduction of the designated hitter rule in 1973, which encouraged AL managers to largely abandon "smallball" tactics.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Though both leagues agreed to be jointly governed by a commissioner in 1920, they remained separate business entities with their own presidents and management.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] This was the case until after the 1999 season, when the American League legally merged with the National League under the auspices of Major League Baseball, which now operates much like other North American professional sports leagues, albeit with two "leagues" instead of "conferences".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Originally a minor league known as the Western League, which existed from 1885 to 1899 with teams in mostly Great Lakes states, the league changed its name to the American League for the 1900 season and the next year developed into a second major league as a competitor to the older National League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] This was prompted by the NL dropping four teams following the 1899 season after having absorbed its previous rival, the American Association, which disbanded in 1891 after ten seasons.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In its early history of the late 1880s, the minor Western League struggled until 1894, when Ban Johnson became the president of the league.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Johnson pushed the league to rise to major league status, after the name change to the American League was decided in a league meeting in Milwaukee, Wisconsin, at the former Republican Hotel.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] A historical marker is at the intersection of North Dr.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Drive and West Kilbourn Avenue where the hotel once stood.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In March 1904, Johnson moved the league's headquarters from Chicago to New York.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Babe Ruth, noted as one of the most prolific hitters in Major League Baseball history, spent the majority of his career in the American League with the Boston Red Sox and the New York Yankees.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] From 1973 to 2022 The American League had one notable difference versus the rival National League, as it had the designated hitter rule.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Under the rule, a team may use a batter in its lineup who is not in the field defensively, replacing the pitcher in the batting order, compared to the old rule that made it mandatory for the pitcher to bat.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In the last two decades, the season schedule has allowed occasional interleague play.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In 1969, the AL (and NL) were divided into East and West divisions, with a postseason playoff series for the pennant and the right to play in the World Series.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Until the late 1970s, league umpires working behind home plate wore large, balloon-style chest protectors worn outside the shirt or coat, while their colleagues in the National League wore chest protectors inside the shirt or coat.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In 1977, new umpires (including Steve Palermo) had to wear the inside chest protector, although those on staff wearing the outside protector could continue to do so.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Most umpires made the switch to the inside protector, led by Don Denkinger in 1975 and Jim Evans the next year, although several did not, including Bill Haller, Russ Goetz, George Maloney, Bill Kunkel and Jerry Neudecker, who became the last full-time MLB umpire to use the outside protector in 1985.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In 1998, the newly franchised Tampa Bay Devil Rays joined the league, and the Arizona Diamondbacks joined the National League: i.e., each league added a fifteenth team.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] An odd number of teams per league meant that at least one team in each league would have to be idle on any given day, or alternatively, that odd team out would have had to play an interleague game against its counterpart in the other league.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The initial plan was to have three five-team divisions per league with inter-league play year-round—possibly as many as 30 interleague games per team each year.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] For various reasons, it soon seemed more practical to have an even number of teams in both leagues.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The Milwaukee Brewers agreed to change leagues to become the National League's 16th team, moving from the AL Central to the NL Central.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] At the same time, the Detroit Tigers were moved from the AL East to the AL Central, making room for the Devil Rays in the East.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Even after expansion, the American League then continued with 14 teams.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] This situation changed again in 2013 when the Houston Astros moved from the National League Central division to the American League West.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The Astros had been in the NL for 51 years since beginning as an expansion team in 1962.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Since their move, both leagues now consist of 15 teams.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] For the first 96 years, American League teams faced their National League counterparts only in exhibition games or in the World Series.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Beginning in 1997, interleague games have been played during the regular season and count in the standings.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] As part of the agreement instituting interleague play, the designated-hitter rule was used only in games where the American League team is the home team, until the 2022 season, when the universal DH rule was implemented.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In 2023, American League teams played 46 regular season interleague games against all 15 National League teams, 23 at home and 23 on the road.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] In 2000, the American League ended its status as a legally independent entity when the American and National Leagues were both merged into the legal entity Major League Baseball (MLB).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] This left MLB as a single league, divided into two parts, also called leagues.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] This change in legal status had no effect on play, scheduling, and so forth.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] There were eight charter teams in 1901, the league's first year as a major league, and the next year the original Milwaukee Brewers (not to be confused with the current Milwaukee Brewers) moved to St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Louis Browns, and the year after the New York Highlanders replaced the disbanded original Baltimore Orioles.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Those eight franchises constituted the league for 52 seasons until the Browns moved to Baltimore and took up the Orioles name.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The first line is the transformation of the American League (AL) to a major league in 1901.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The second line is the beginning of the expansion era in 1961.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The third line marks the legal merger of the American and National Leagues into a single Major League Baseball in 2000.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] World Series championships are shown with a "•", American League Pennants before the World Series are shown with a "#", and American League Pennants who lost the World Series are shown with a "^".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] No World Series was played in 1904, so the pennant winners for each league are indicated.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Due to the 1994–95 Major League Baseball strike, there were no pennant or World Series winners in 1994, so this year is left blank.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] Following the 1999 season, the American and National Leagues were merged with Major League Baseball, and the leagues ceased to exist as business entities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/american-league] The position of the American League President and National League President became honorary.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] An **amusement park** is a park that features various attractions, such as rides and games, and events for entertainment purposes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A **theme park** is a type of amusement park that bases its structures and attractions around a central theme, often featuring multiple areas with different themes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Unlike temporary and mobile funfairs and carnivals, amusement parks are stationary and built for long-lasting operation.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] They are more elaborate than city parks and playgrounds, usually providing attractions that cater to a variety of age groups.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] While amusement parks often contain themed areas, theme parks place a heavier focus with more intricately designed themes that revolve around a particular subject or group of subjects.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement parks evolved from European fairs, pleasure gardens, and large picnic areas, which were created for people's recreation.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] World's fairs and other types of international expositions also influenced the emergence of the amusement park industry.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Bakken ("The Hill") in Klampenborg, Denmark, Wurstelprater in Vienna, Austria, and Tivoli Gardens in Copenhagen, Denmark are the three oldest operating amusement parks in the world.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Lake Compounce, which opened in 1846, is considered the oldest continuously operating amusement park in North America.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The amusement park evolved from traditions in the European Middle Ages.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] An amusement park is a contemporary arrangement, designed to combine components of a fair, carnival, and theme park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] An early example of an amusement park is the Bartholomew Fair.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the 18th and 19th centuries, they had evolved into places of entertainment for the masses, where the public could view freak shows, acrobatics, conjuring, and juggling, take part in competitions and walk through menageries.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] This inaugurated the era of the modern funfair ride, as the working classes were increasingly able to spend their surplus wages on entertainment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The second influence was the pleasure garden.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Bakken ("The Hill"), the world's oldest amusement park, opened in mainland Europe in 1583.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It is located north of Copenhagen in Klampenborg, Denmark.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In many European countries, traditional amusement parks evolved from pleasure gardens, combining mechanical rides with landscaped spaces, live music, and seasonal festivities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Another example in early gardens was the Vauxhall Gardens, founded in 1661, in London.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the late 18th century, the site had an admission fee for its many attractions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It regularly drew enormous crowds, with its paths often noted for romantic assignations; tightrope walkers, hot air balloon ascents, concerts and fireworks providing amusement.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Although the gardens were originally designed for the elites, they soon became places of great social diversity.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Public firework displays were put on at Marylebone Gardens, and Cremorne Gardens offered music, dancing, and animal acrobatics displays.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Prater, located in Vienna, Austria, began as a royal hunting ground which was opened in 1766 for public enjoyment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] There followed coffee-houses and cafés, which led to the beginnings of the Wurstelprater as an amusement park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The concept of a fixed park for amusement was further developed with the beginning of the world's fairs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first World fair began in 1851 with the construction of the landmark Crystal Palace in London, England.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The purpose of the exposition was to celebrate the industrial achievement of the nations of the world and it was designed to educate and entertain the visitors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the United States, cities and businesses also saw the world's fair as a way of demonstrating economic and industrial success.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The World's Columbian Exposition of 1893 in Chicago, Illinois was an early precursor to the modern amusement park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The fair was an enclosed site, that merged entertainment, engineering and education to entertain the masses.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It set out to bedazzle the visitors, and successfully did so with a blaze of lights from the "White City".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] To make sure that the fair was a financial success, the planners included a dedicated amusement concessions area called the Midway Plaisance.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Rides from this fair captured the imagination of the visitors and of amusement parks around the world, such as the first steel Ferris wheel, which was found in many other amusement areas, such as the Prater by 1896.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Also, the experience of the enclosed ideal city with wonder, rides, culture and progress (electricity), was based on the creation of an illusory place.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The "midway" introduced at the Columbian Exposition would become a standard part of most amusement parks, fairs, carnivals, and circuses.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The midway contained not only the rides, but other concessions and entertainments such as shooting galleries, penny arcades, games of chance, and shows.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Many modern amusement parks evolved from earlier pleasure resorts that had become popular with the public for day-trips or weekend holidays, for example, seaside areas such as Blackpool, United Kingdom and Coney Island, United States.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The trick was getting the public to the seaside or resort location.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] For Coney Island in Brooklyn, New York, on the Atlantic Ocean, a horse-drawn streetcar line brought pleasure seekers to the beach beginning in 1829.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1875, a million passengers rode the Coney Island Railroad, and in 1876 two million visited Coney Island.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Hotels and amusements were built to accommodate both the upper classes and the working class at the beach.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Its first amusement ride, a carousel, was installed in 1876; the first roller coaster, the "Switchback Railway", in 1884.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In England, Blackpool was a popular beachside location beginning in the 1700s.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It rose to prominence as a seaside resort with the completion in 1846 of a branch line to Blackpool from Poulton on the main Preston and Wyre Joint Railway line.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A sudden influx of visitors, arriving by rail, provided the motivation for entrepreneurs to build accommodation and create new attractions, leading to more visitors and a rapid cycle of growth throughout the 1850s and 1860s.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1879, large parts of the promenade at Blackpool were wired.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The lighting and its accompanying pageants reinforced Blackpool's status as the North of England's most prominent holiday resort, and its specifically working class character.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It was the forerunner of the present-day Blackpool Illuminations.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the 1890s, the town had a population of 35,000, and could accommodate 250,000 holidaymakers.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The number of annual visitors, many staying for a week, was estimated at three million.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the final decade of the 19th century, electric trolley lines were developed in many large American cities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Companies that established the trolley lines also developed trolley parks as destinations of these lines.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some of these parks were developed in resort locations, such as bathing resorts at the seaside in New Jersey and New York.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A premiere example in New Jersey was Atlantic City, a famous vacation resort.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Entrepreneurs erected amusement parks on piers that extended from the boardwalk out over the ocean.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first of several was the Ocean Pier in 1891, followed later by the Steel Pier in 1898, both of which boasted rides and attractions typical of that time, such as Midway-style games and electric trolley rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The boardwalk also had the first Roundabout installed in 1892 by William Somers, a wooden predecessor to the Ferris Wheel.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Somers installed two others in Asbury Park, New Jersey and Coney Island, New York.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Another early park was the Eldorado Amusement Park that opened in 1891 on the banks of the Hudson River, overlooking New York City.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first permanent enclosed entertainment area, regulated by a single company, was founded in Coney Island in 1895: Sea Lion Park at Coney Island in Brooklyn.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] This park was one of the first to charge admission fee to get into the park in addition to sell tickets for rides within the park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1897, Sea Lion Park was joined by Steeplechase Park, the first of three major amusement parks that opened in the Coney Island area.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] George Tilyou designed the park to provide thrills and entertainment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The combination of the nearby population center of New York City and the ease of access to the area made Coney Island the embodiment of the American amusement park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Coney Island also featured Luna Park (1903) and Dreamland (1904).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Coney Island was a huge success and by the year 1910 attendance on days could reach a million people.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Fueled by the efforts of Frederick Ingersoll who borrowed the name, other "Luna Parks" were quickly erected worldwide and opened to rave reviews.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first amusement park in England, Blackpool Pleasure Beach, opened in 1896, developed by W.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1904, Sir Hiram Maxim's Captive Flying Machine was introduced; he had designed an early aircraft powered by steam engines that had been unsuccessful and instead opened up a pleasure ride of flying carriages that revolved around a central pylon.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Other rides included the 'Grotto' (a fantasy ride), 'River Caves' (a scenic railway), water chutes and a tobogganing tower.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Fire was a constant threat in those days, as much of the construction within the amusement parks of the era was wooden.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1911, Dreamland was the first Coney Island amusement park to completely burn down; in 1944, Luna Park also burned to the ground.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Most of Ingersoll's Luna Parks were similarly destroyed, usually by arson, before his death in 1927.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] During the Gilded Age, many Americans began working fewer hours and had more disposable income.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] With new-found money and time to spend on leisure activities, Americans sought new venues for entertainment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement parks, set up outside major cities and in rural areas, emerged to meet this new economic opportunity.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] These parks served as a source of fantasy and escape from real life.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the early 1900s, hundreds of amusement parks were operating in the United States and Canada.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Trolley parks stood outside many cities.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Parks like Atlanta's Ponce de Leon and Idora Park, near Youngstown, OH, took passengers to traditionally popular picnic grounds, which by the late 1890s also often included rides like the Giant Swing, Carousel, and Shoot-the-Chutes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] These amusement parks were often based on nationally known parks or world's fairs: they had names like Coney Island, White City, Luna Park, or Dreamland.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The American Gilded Age was, in fact, amusement parks' Golden Age that reigned until the late 1920s.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The Golden Age of amusement parks also included the advent of the kiddie park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Founded in 1925, the original Kiddie Park is located in San Antonio, Texas, and is still in operation as of 2022.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The kiddie parks became popular all over America after World War II.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] This era saw the development of new innovations in roller coasters that included extreme drops and speeds to thrill the riders.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the end of World War I, people seemed to want an even more exciting entertainment, a need met by roller coasters.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Although the development of the automobile provided people with more options for satisfying their entertainment needs, the amusement parks after the war continued to be successful, while urban amusement parks saw declining attendance.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The 1920s is more properly known as the Golden Age of roller coasters, being the decade of frenetic building for these rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In England, Dreamland Margate opened in 1880 with Frederick Savage's carousel the first amusement ride installed.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1920 the Scenic Railway rollercoaster opened to the public with great success, carrying half a million passengers in its first year.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park also installed other rides common to the time including a smaller roller coaster, the Joy Wheel, Miniature Railway, The Whip and the River Caves.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A ballroom was constructed on the site of the Skating Rink in 1920 and in 1923 a Variety Cinema was built on the site.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Between 1920 and 1935 over £500,000 was invested in the site, constantly adding new rides and facilities and culminating in the construction of the Dreamland Cinema complex in 1934 which stands to this day.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Until 2011, the Blackpool Pleasure Beach ranked among the top free of charge attractions in Britain.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Blackpool Pleasure beach was developed continuously, requiring frequent large-scale investments.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The construction of many new rides could be counted on.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Rides included the Virginia Reel, Whip, Noah's Ark, Big Dipper and Dodgems.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the 1920s the "Casino Building" was built, which remains to this day.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1923, land was reclaimed from the sea front.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It was at this period that the park moved to its 44-acre (18 ha) current location above what became Watson Road, which was built under the Pleasure Beach in 1932.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] During this time Joseph Emberton, an architect famous for his work in the amusement trade was brought in to redesign the architectural style of the Pleasure Beach rides, working on the "Grand National" roller coaster, "Noah's Ark" and the Casino building to name a few.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The Great Depression of the 1930s and World War II during the 1940s saw the decline of the amusement park industry.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] War caused the affluent urban population to move to the suburbs, television became a source of entertainment, and families went to amusement parks less often.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the 1950s, factors such as urban decay, crime, and even desegregation in the ghettos led to changing patterns in how people chose to spend their free time.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Many of the older, traditional amusement parks closed or burned to the ground.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Many would be taken out by the wrecking ball to make way for suburb and housing and development.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1964, Steeplechase Park, once the king of all amusement parks, closed down for good.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The traditional amusement parks which survived, for example, Kennywood, in West Mifflin, Pennsylvania, and Cedar Point, in Sandusky, Ohio, did so in spite of the odds.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Inspired by the layout of Tivoli Gardens theme park in Copenhagen, Denmark, in 1951, Walt Disney came up with the idea of having an amusement park next to the studios in Burbank.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park would have been called Mickey Mouse Park, built across the street with a western area featuring a steam driven paddleboat, a turn of the century town, and a midway.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It was rejected by the Burbank city council in fear of a carnival atmosphere.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1952, he created WED Enterprises to design the park, which was now to be built in Anaheim, and in 1953, was able to convince the bankers on funding the park with the help of a studio artist, Herb Ryman, by making an aerial drawing of Disneyland.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By July 1954, construction had started with a deadline of one year.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disneyland opened on July 17, 1955, and two months after the park opened, it welcomed its one millionth guest.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Because of the financial success of Disneyland, the amusement industry was reinvigorated.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] What became Busch Gardens Tampa opened in 1959 as a garden and bird sanctuary.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Six Flags Over Texas opened in 1961, themed to the six countries that ruled over Texas.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1964, Universal Studios Hollywood opened to the public with a studio tour of their backlot that had multiple adventure scenes and became a proper theme park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] That same year, SeaWorld San Diego opened and displayed many varieties of aquatic and marine life.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Initially meant to house Walt Disney's dream idea, EPCOT (Experimental Prototype Community Of Tomorrow), Disney executives decided to settle on building the park first in Walt Disney World and the city later.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] After six years of construction, Walt Disney World opened to the public on October 1, 1971.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1982, Walt Disney Productions opened the second Walt Disney World park, EPCOT Center, based on Walt Disney's futurist ideals and World Fairs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Like a World's Fair, the park would display the latest technologies in an area called Future World, and the cultural pavilions in World Showcase.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1987, Disney announced that it would open its third Disney World park, Disney-MGM Studios in 1989, which would have a working backlot.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, Universal knew that its Californian backlot tour would not work as a standalone attraction next to Disney World (especially now as Disney built one in Disney-MGM).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] So it divided up the segments of its California tour into individual attractions, such as Jaws, Disaster!, and Kongfrontation.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disney-MGM Studios opened it on May 1, 1989, with two major attractions: The Backlot Tour and The Great Movie Ride.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The concept for the park started out as an EPCOT pavilion, but was turned into a park as a "half day" attraction—a complement to the rest of the resort.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The rest of the park was themed to 1930s Hollywood and featured lost parts of Hollywood like the Brown Derby.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Universal Studios Florida opened on June 7, 1990 (delayed by one year) to great fanfare, but the primary attractions were experiencing severe technical difficulties.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] All three of the park's major attractions (Jaws, Disaster!, and Kongfrontation) were not working and suffered major technical difficulties.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disaster! and Kongfrontation were fixed by the end of June, but Jaws had to be rebuilt and reopened three years later.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, Universal learned from opening day and started conducting exit surveys and special ticket deals.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A recession in the French economy and the immense public backlash against the park led to financial hardship, putting the park into debt.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, this did not stop Disney from expanding Disney-MGM Studios with The Twilight Zone Tower of Terror, in 1994, and building their fourth Walt Disney World park, Disney's Animal Kingdom.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the early 1990s, after the opening of Universal Studios Florida, Universal sought to build a second theme park, one aimed more towards children and their families.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Universal acquired the theme park rights to many properties including DC and Dr.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1999, Universal Studios opened Universal Studios Islands of Adventure under the new resort name Universal Studios Escape.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park was allegedly designed by former Disney Imagineers who left after the financial disaster of Disneyland Paris.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the late 80s, the Oriental Land Company (the owners and operators of Tokyo Disneyland resort which opened in 1983) wanted a second park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] None of the current non-Magic Kingdom parks satisfied the Japanese, but one concept thrown away for Disneyland's second gate inspired a new one: DisneySea.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Tokyo DisneySea is themed after stories based on the ocean and nautical adventure.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It was constructed at a cost of ¥335 billion and opened on September 4, 2001.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park's two signature attractions are a modernized version of 20,000 Leagues Under The Sea and Journey To The Center of The Earth.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the early 1990s, Michael Eisner wanted to make Disneyland in the image of Walt Disney World's resort style.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Plans were made for multiple hotels, such as one based on the Grand Floridian Hotel, and a new west coast version of EPCOT, called WESTCOT.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] WESTCOT never came to be due to local opposition from residents, rising costs, and the financial fallout of Disneyland Paris.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] After a corporate retreat in Colorado, Disney executives decided to make a park themed to California so that guests could experience all of California within the confines of the Disneyland Resort and would be built across from Disneyland on its 100-acre parking lot.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disney's California Adventure would be the largest disaster Disney ever created because unlike Disneyland, it would be set in the modern day and spoof modern-day California with its cheap, insincere, and flat backdrops.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park would be adult focused, sell fine food, and serve alcohol.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] When the park opened on February 8, 2001, it received a chilly reception for its lack of attractions, poor environment (for example, Hollywood Studios Backlot was themed to a modern-day movie backlot of modern-day Hollywood), and overemphasis on retail and dining.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Walt Disney Studios Park in Paris was the second Disneyland Paris park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disney had to build a second park or risk losing the land to the French government.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park opened March 16, 2002, with only three rides and California Adventure style theming.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, Hong Kong Disneyland was higher quality than the other black sheep, but still lacked the number of attractions that was needed, just like California Adventure and Walt Disney Studios Park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It opened on September 12, 2005, with only four lands, and had exorbitant wait times on opening day for everything from rides to food.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the early 2000s, the Harry Potter book series written by J.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Rowling had become a pop culture phenomenon.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Universal and Disney entered a bidding war over the theme park rights to the books, but Disney seemed to have won after Rowling signed a letter of intent with Disney.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, Rowling was disappointed with Disney's small-scale plans to install an omnimover attraction themed to the Defense Against the Dark Arts class with one shop and one restaurant in the former submarine lagoon at Magic Kingdom.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] She was also displeased with the lack of creative control she had and exited the deal.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] She went to Universal next and was also displeased with the initial plan to redress the Islands of Adventure's Lost Continent area.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Rowling wrestled creative control from Universal and forced them to make the land a full scale, realistic re-creation of Hogsmeade and Hogwarts without being a refurbishment of an existing area.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The project was announced in 2007 and in 2010 the land was opened to the public and made Universal Orlando.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The amusement park industry's offerings range from immersive theme parks such as Warner Bros.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] World Abu Dhabi, the Disneyland Resort and Universal Orlando Resort to thrilling coaster parks such as the Six Flags parks and United Parks & Resorts parks.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Countless smaller ventures exist across the United States and around the world.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Simpler theme parks directly aimed at smaller children have also emerged, such as Legoland.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Examples of amusement parks in shopping malls exist in West Edmonton Mall, Pier 39 and Mall of America.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Family fun parks starting as miniature golf courses have begun to grow to include batting cages, go-karts, bumper cars, bumper boats and water slides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some of these parks have grown to include even roller coasters, and traditional amusement parks now also have these competition areas in addition to their thrill rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 2015, theme parks in the United States had a revenue of US$8 billion and theme parks in China had a revenue of US$4.6 billion, with China expected to overtake the United States by 2020.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some parks use rides and attractions for educational purposes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] There are also Holy Land USA and the Holy Land Experience, which are theme parks built to inspire Christian piety.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Dinosaur World entertains families with dinosaurs in natural settings, while the SeaWorld and Busch Gardens parks also offer educational experiences, with each of the parks housing several thousand animals, fish and other sea life in dozens of attractions and exhibits focusing on animal education.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Created in 1977, the Puy du Fou is a much-celebrated theme park in Vendée, France.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It is centered around European, French and local history.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It received several international prizes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some theme parks did evolve from more traditional amusement park enterprises, such as Knott's Berry Farm.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the 1920s, Walter Knott and his family sold berries from a roadside stand, which grew to include a restaurant serving fried chicken dinners.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Within a few years, lines outside the restaurant were often several hours long.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] To entertain the waiting crowds, Walter Knott built a Ghost Town in 1940, using buildings relocated from real old west towns such as the Calico, California, ghost town and Prescott, Arizona.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1968, the Knott family fenced the farm, charged admission for the first time, and Knott's Berry Farm officially became a theme park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Because of its long history, Knott's Berry Farm currently claims to be "America's First Theme Park".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Knott's Berry Farm is now owned by Six Flags Entertainment Company.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Lake Compounce in Bristol, Connecticut, may be the true oldest continuously operating amusement park in the United States, open since 1846.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Santa Claus Town, which opened in Santa Claus, Indiana, in 1935 and included Santa's Candy Castle and other Santa Claus-themed attractions is considered the first themed attraction in the United States: a precursor to the modern day theme park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Santa Claus Land (renamed Holiday World in 1984) opened in 1946 in Santa Claus, Indiana, and many people will argue that it was the first true Theme Park despite Knott's history.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the 1950s the Herschend family took over operation of the tourist attraction, Marvel Cave near Branson, Missouri.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Over the next decade they modernized the cave, which led to large numbers of people waiting to take the tour.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The Herschend family opened a recreation of the old mining town that once existed atop Marvel Cave.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The small village eventually became the theme park, Silver Dollar City.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park is still owned and operated by the Herschends and the family has several other parks including Dollywood, Kentucky Kingdom and Wild Adventures.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first regional amusement park, as well as the first Six Flags park, Six Flags Over Texas was officially opened in 1961 in Arlington, Texas.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The first Six Flags amusement park was the vision of Angus Wynne Jr. and helped create the modern, competitive amusement park industry.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the late 1950s, Wynne visited Disneyland and was inspired to create an affordable, closer, and larger amusement park that would be filled with fantasy.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] He followed in the steps of Disney and had subdivisions within the park that reflected different lands.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The subdivisions included the Old South and other sections that referenced Wynne's background.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By 1968, the second Six Flags park, Six Flags Over Georgia, opened, and in 1971, Six Flags Over Mid-America (now Six Flags St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Also in 1971 was the opening of the Walt Disney World resort complex in Florida.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1985, a theme park called Santa Claus Village was opened in Rovaniemi, Finland near the Arctic Circle, which led the city to trademark itself as the "official hometown of Santa Claus" in 2009.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In 1991 Warner Bros. in partnership with Village Roadshow, opened their own Warner Bros.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It is the only Movie-Related theme park in Australia.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Warner Bros. continued their theme park ventures and opened Warner Bros.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] World Abu Dhabi in UAE and Parque Warner Madrid in Spain.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement parks collect much of their revenue from admission fees paid by guests attending the park.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Other revenue sources include parking fees, food and beverage sales and souvenirs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In amusement parks, using the pay-as-you-go scheme, guests enter the park at little or no charge.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The guests are then required to purchase rides individually, either at the attraction's entrance or by purchasing ride tickets (or a similar exchange method, like a token).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The cost of the attraction is often based on its complexity or popularity.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] For example, one guest might pay one ticket to ride a carousel, but also four tickets to ride a roller coaster.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The park may allow guests to purchase a pass providing unlimited admissions to all attractions within the park for a specified duration of time.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A wristband or pass is then shown at the attraction entrance to gain admission.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disneyland opened in 1955, using the pay-as-you-go format.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Initially, guests paid the ride admission fees at the attractions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Within a short time, the problems of handling such large amounts of coins led to the development of a ticket system that, while now out of use, is still part of the amusement-park lexicon.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In this new format, guests purchased ticket books that contained a number of tickets, labeled "A", "B" and "C." Rides and attractions using an "A-ticket" were generally simple, with "B-tickets" and "C-tickets" used for the larger, more popular rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Later, the "D-ticket" was added, then finally the "E-ticket", which was used on the biggest and most elaborate rides, like Space Mountain.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Smaller tickets could be traded up for use on larger rides, for example two or three A-tickets would equal a single B-ticket.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Disneyland, as well as the Magic Kingdom at Walt Disney World, eventually abandoned this practice in 1982.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] An amusement park using the pay-one-price scheme charges guests a single admission fee.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Guests are subsequently given access to most of the attractions, usually including flagship roller coasters, in the park as often as they wish during their visit.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Parks with a pay-one-price admission format often have attractions that are not included in the admission charge; these are called "up-charge attractions" and may include Skycoasters or go-kart tracks, or games of skill where prizes are won.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] World, and Parque Warner Madrid, follow this scheme.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] When Angus Wynne, founder of Six Flags Over Texas, first visited Disneyland upon its opening in 1955, he noted that park's pay-as-you-go format as a reason to make his park pay-one-price.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] He thought that a family would be more likely to visit his park if they knew, up front, how much it would cost to attend.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Mechanized thrill rides are a defining feature of amusement park attractions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Early rides include the carousel, which originally developed from cavalry training methods first used in the Middle Ages.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] By the 19th century, carousels were common in parks around the world.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Another such ride which shaped the future of the amusement park was the roller coaster.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] These crude and temporarily built curiosities, known as *Russian Mountains*, were the beginning of the search for even more thrilling amusement park rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The Columbian Exposition of 1893 was a particularly fertile testing ground for amusement rides and included some that the public had never seen before, such as the world's first Ferris wheel, one of the most recognized products of the fair.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] In the present day, many rides of various types are set around a specific theme.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Parks contains a mixture of attractions which can be divided into several categories.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Flat rides are usually considered to be those that move their passengers in a plane generally parallel to the ground.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] There is a core set of flat rides which most amusement parks have, including the Enterprise, Tilt-A-Whirl, Gravitron, chairswing, swinging inverter ship, twister, and top spin.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] However, there is constant innovation, with new variations on ways to spin and throw passengers around appearing in an effort to keep attracting customers.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Manufactures such as Huss and Zamperla specialise in creating flat rides among other amusement attractions.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement parks often feature multiple roller coasters of primarily timber or steel construction.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Fundamentally, a roller coaster ride is one in which a specialized railroad system with steep drops and sharp curves, passengers sit and are restrained in cars, usually with two or more cars joined to form a train.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some roller coasters feature one or more inversions (such as vertical loops) which turn the riders upside down.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Over the years there have been many roller coaster manufacturers with a variety of types of roller coasters.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement park railways have had a long and varied history in American amusement parks as well as overseas.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some of the earliest park trains were not really trains; they were trolleys, which brought park patrons to the parks on regular rail lines from the cities to the end of the rail lines where the parks were located.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some older parks, such as Kennywood in Pennsylvania, were referred to as trolley parks.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] The earliest park trains that only operated on lines within the park's boundaries, such as the one on the ridable miniature Zephyr Railroad at Dorney Park & Wildwater Kingdom, were mostly custom-built.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A few parks trains, including Disneyland Railroad, Walt Disney World Railroad, and Dollywood Express, operate using locomotives that had working careers on common carrier railways.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement park railways tend to be narrow-gauge, meaning the space between their rails is smaller than that of 4 ft 8+1⁄2 in (1,435 mm) standard gauge railroads.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Some specific narrow gauges that are common on amusement park railroads are 3 ft (914 mm) gauge, 2 ft 6 in (762 mm) gauge, 2 ft (610 mm) gauge, and 15 in (381 mm) gauge.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Amusement parks with water resources generally feature a few water rides, such as the log flume, bumper boats, rapids and rowing boats.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Such rides are usually gentler and shorter than roller coasters and many are suitable for all ages.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Water rides are especially popular on hot days.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Overlapping with both train rides and water rides, dark rides are enclosed attractions in which patrons travel in guided vehicles along a predetermined path, through an array of illuminated scenes which may include lighting effects, animation, music and recorded dialogue, and other special effects.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] A haunted house is an attraction that intends to scare its guests for its thrill factor.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] It usually is overlapped with dark rides.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Most open in the Halloween season but some are year-round.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Most include actors, lighting, darkness, fog and animatronics.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Ferris wheels are the most common type of amusement ride at state fairs and county fairs in the US.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Transport rides are used to take large numbers of guests from one area to another, as an alternative to walking, especially for parks that are large or separated into distant areas.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Transport rides include chairlifts, monorails, aerial trams, and escalators.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Ocean Park Hong Kong is well known for its 1.5-kilometre (0.9 mi) cable car connecting the Lowland and Headland areas of the park, and for having the world's second longest outdoor escalator in the Headland.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Both transportation links provide scenic views of the park's hilly surroundings and, while originally intended for practicality rather than thrills or enjoyment, have become significant park attractions in their own right.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] There are food stands at amusement parks which serve a variety of food and beverages.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] They offer snack items like cotton candy, ice cream, fried dough, funnel cake, candy apples or caramel apples and french fries.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Meal items may include pizza, hamburgers, hot dogs, and chicken.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Beverages may include soda, coffee, tea, and lemonade.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Junk food items like deep fried candy bars, the deep-fried Twinkie, Dippin' Dots ice cream, the blooming onion, and "deep-fried butter on-a-stick" are some of the delicacies that can be found at food stands.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/amusement-park] Local and regional specialties, along with ethnic foods, are often available such as Empanadas and Tacos.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1852, German American brewer and saloon operator George Schneider opened the Bavarian Brewery on Carondelet Avenue (later known as South Broadway) between Dorcas and Lynch streets in South St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Schneider's Brewery expanded in 1856 to a new brewhouse near Eighth and Crittenden streets; however, the following year, financial problems forced the sale of the brewery to various owners during the late 1850s.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1860, the brewery was purchased on the brink of bankruptcy by William D'Oench, a local pharmacist, and Eberhard Anheuser, a prosperous German-born soap manufacturer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] D'Oench was the silent partner in the business until 1869 when he sold his half-interest in the company to Anheuser's son-in-law Adolphus Busch.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] From 1860 to 1875, the brewery was known as E.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser & Co., and from 1875 to 1879 as the E.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Busch, a wholesaler who had immigrated to St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis from Germany in 1857, had married Eberhard Anheuser's daughter, Lilly, in 1861.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Following his service in the American Civil War, Busch began working as a salesman for the Anheuser Brewery.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Busch purchased D'Oench's share of the company in 1869, and he assumed the role of company secretary from that time until the death of his father-in-law.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Adolphus Busch was the first American brewer to use pasteurization to keep beer fresh; the first to use mechanical refrigeration and refrigerated railroad cars, which he introduced in 1876; and the first to bottle beer extensively.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] By 1877, the company owned a fleet of 40 refrigerated railroad cars to transport beer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Expanding the company's distribution range led to increased demand for Anheuser products, and the company substantially expanded its facilities in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The expansions led production to increase from 31,500 barrels in 1875 to more than 200,000 in 1881.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] To streamline the company's refrigerator car operations and achieve vertical integration, Busch established the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis Refrigerator Car Company in 1878, which was charged with building, selling, and leasing refrigerator cars; by 1883, the company owned 200 cars, and by 1888 it owned 850.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] To serve these cars and switch them in and out of their St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis brewery, Anheuser-Busch founded the Manufacturers Railway Company in 1887.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The shortline operated until 2011, when Anheuser-Busch shut down its operations.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] During the 1870s, Adolphus Busch toured Europe and studied the changes in brewing methods which were taking place at the time, particularly the success of pilsner beer, which included a popular Budweiser beer brewed in Budweis.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1876, Busch took the already well-known name Budweiser and used it for his new beer, even though his product had no connections to the city of Budweis.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] His company's ability to transport bottled beer made US Budweiser the first national beer brand in the United States, and it was marketed as a "premium" beer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The company was renamed Anheuser-Busch Brewing Association in 1879; in 1880, Adolphus Busch became company president upon Anheuser's death.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The Busch family fully controlled the company through the generations until Anheuser-Busch's sale to InBev in 2008.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] During the 1880s and 1890s, Busch introduced a series of advertisements and marketing giveaways for the company, including bottle openers, calendars, corkscrews, pocketknives, postcards, and prints.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Among the most well-known of these giveaways was *Custer's Last Fight*, a lithograph print of a painting by St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] As a marketing tactic, Busch distributed thousands of copies of the print to bars in 1896, the same year Anheuser-Busch introduced its new "super-premium" brand, Michelob.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] At the turn of the 20th century, Anheuser-Busch continued to expand its production facilities to keep up with demand.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1905, the company built a new stockhouse in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis, and by 1907 it produced nearly 1.6 million barrels of beer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] As demands for the prohibition of alcohol in the United States grew, Anheuser-Busch began producing non-alcoholic and low-alcoholic beverages (known as near beer); the most successful of these was Bevo, a malt beverage introduced in 1908.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] After the death of Adolphus Busch in 1913, control of the company passed to his son, August Anheuser Busch Sr., who continued to combat the rise of prohibitionists.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] As part of an effort to improve the respectability of drinking, August Busch built three upscale restaurants in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis during the 1910s: the Stork Inn, the Gretchen Inn (now known as the Feasting Fox), and the Bevo Mill.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] As with all breweries in the country, the Temperance movement and eventual Prohibition in the United States dealt a major blow to the company in the 1910s through the 1930s.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Some of the products sold by Anheuser-Busch to survive during Prohibition included brewer's yeast, malt extract, ice cream, and Bevo, a nonalcoholic malt beverage, or "near beer".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1957, Anheuser-Busch became the largest brewer in the United States.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1981, Anheuser-Busch International, Inc., was established as a subsidiary responsible for the company's international operations and equity investments.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Prior to its 2008 acquisition, Anheuser-Busch operated 15 breweries internationally: 14 in China and one in the United Kingdom.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1997, Chinese production of Anheuser-Busch products began after the company's purchase of a local brewery; later, the company operated both Budweiser Wuhan International Brewing Company and Harbin Brewery, which Anheuser-Busch fully acquired in 2004.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In the United Kingdom, the Budweiser Stag Brewing Company produced and packaged Budweiser at the Stag Brewery in Mortlake.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] At one time, Anheuser-Busch International also held investments in Grupo Modelo in Mexico Tsingtao Brewery in China; Anheuser-Busch also held investments in Redhook Ale Brewery of Seattle, Washington and Widmer Brothers Brewery of Portland, Oregon.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] After the 2008 acquisition, most international operations were transferred to AB InBev zones where the interests are located.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] InBev also stated that the merger would not result in any U.S. brewery closures and they would attempt to retain management and board members from both companies.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On June 25, 2008, Anheuser-Busch officially announced that they would reject InBev's offer and provide a restructuring of the company to maintain shareholders and United States World Headquarters in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On July 1, 2008, InBev urged Anheuser-Busch shareholders to vote in favor of the buyout as InBev felt the offer of $65 per share should be considered a reasonable offer in view of the falling stock market.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The company had previously filed suit in Delaware, after the rejection of their offer, to ensure that the stockholders could oust Anheuser-Busch's 13 board members.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On July 7, 2008, Anheuser-Busch filed a lawsuit against InBev to stop them from soliciting the support of shareholders, stating that the company's offer is an illegal scheme.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] InBev was also accused of concealing that they do business in Cuba, which might have created additional obstacles to their efforts to operate in the United States.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On July 13, 2008, Anheuser-Busch and InBev said they had agreed to a deal, pending shareholder and regulatory approval, for InBev to purchase the American icon at $70 per share, creating a new company to be named Anheuser-Busch InBev.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch would get two seats on the combined board of directors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The all-cash agreement, almost $52 billion in total equity, created the world's largest brewer, uniting the maker of Budweiser and Michelob with the producer of Beck's, Stella Artois, Hoegaarden, Leffe, Bass, Labatt and Brahma.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The two companies had combined yearly sales of more than $36.4 billion, surpassing the current No.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Grupo Modelo took InBev to arbitration for more than a year and a half after the deal was completed, attempting to block the deal.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On October 7, 2009, parent company Anheuser-Busch InBev announced plans to sell the theme parks division to The Blackstone Group for up to US$2.7 billion.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In July 2010, a panel decided that the takeover did not violate Anheuser-Busch's agreement with Modelo.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On November 18, 2008, the hostile takeover was completed, and the parent corporation was renamed Anheuser-Busch InBev; Anheuser-Busch became a wholly owned subsidiary of the new corporation, controlled within the North America zone unit of AB InBev.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] They immediately laid off 1,400 employees and 415 contractors, sold Busch Entertainment Corporation, and sold company-owned aircraft.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis Cardinals baseball games and for Busch Gardens were taken away from employees.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch stopped providing free beer to its employees and visitors to its theme parks.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] These internal changes accompanied changes in its advertising.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] These cost-cutting measures rapidly reduced AB InBev's debt from $56.6 billion in 2008 to $30.1 billion at the end of 2012.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] When the restructuring was complete, only three senior-level Anheuser-Busch managers remained.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] InBev auctioned off several large assets in an effort to pay off debt to the banks that financed the merger.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] It sold Anheuser's 27% stake in China's Tsingtao, sold a few beverage can and lid-making plants to Ball Corporation, and sold its own Korean beer business for $1.8 billion to private equity firm Kohlberg Kravis and Roberts & Co.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] It put the 10 theme parks in Anheuser's Busch Entertainment Unit, which included its three SeaWorld locations, up for sale.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Under InBev, Anheuser-Busch also lengthened accounts payable terms, and introduced zero-based budgeting.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] These changes caused concern from its suppliers when Anheuser-Busch announced it would take 120 days to pay its bills rather than 30 days, taking time to use that money for other purposes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The new payment policy often results in longer periods than 120 days, since the 120 days starts from the end of the month in which the invoice is 'approved' internally, which can be many days/months after an invoice is submitted.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] InBev signed a 10-year lease on 31,500 square feet of office space on Park Avenue in New York, which led to speculation that they would move Anheuser-Busch InBev North American headquarters from St Louis.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In February 2013, a widely publicized lawsuit accused AB InBev of "watering down" products including Budweiser and Michelob.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Such beers are intentionally brewed over-strength and then "watered down" to the intended level, creating a product of equal or greater quality.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch Companies operates as one of several subsidiaries in the North America zone unit of Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV (AB InBev) and it produces and distributes hundreds of products from the AB InBev portfolio.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On October 10, 2016, a $100 billion merger between Anheuser-Busch InBev and SABMiller closed.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The new company is trading as NewbelcoSABMiller.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Michel Doukeris is the current CEO of AB InBev, the parent company of the U.S. operation, and Brendan Whitworth is the current CEO of the Anheuser-Busch subsidiary.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 2008 Anheuser-Busch was acquired by InBev, and the combined company was renamed Anheuser-Busch InBev.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis brewery, which opened in 1852, is a National Historic Landmark District, and includes three buildings listed as National Historic Landmarks.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Public tours of the brewery are offered.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The tour takes visitors through the complex where they can see beer being made and packaged in a working part of the brewery.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The company keeps a rotation of its famous Budweiser Clydesdales at its headquarters, and visitors to the brewery can observe the clydesdales in their exercise field and see their places in the carriage house.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The brewery was designated a National Historic Landmark in 1966.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser Busch owns and operates aluminum can plants (Metal Container Corporation).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] MCC supplies Anheuser Busch breweries and Pepsi Beverages Group fillers across the US.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Suppliers to Anheuser-Busch Companies include Owens-Illinois, which provides glass bottles to several Anheuser-Busch breweries.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch also owns glass production facilities, such as the former Longhorn Glass, which provides glass for the Houston brewery.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch Companies delivers its products to retailers through a network of more than 500 independent wholesalers and 13 wholly owned distributors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On February 20, 1953, Anheuser-Busch purchased the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis Cardinals major league baseball club and owned them until March 21, 1996, when the club was sold to a group of private investors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 1966, Busch Memorial Stadium was paid for and built by the brewery and opened for business; Anheuser-Busch later purchased the stadium in 1981 for $53 million and removed the "Memorial" in its name.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The stadium was demolished in late 2005 and replaced by a new ballpark in 2006.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch signed an agreement to retain the "Busch Stadium" name on the new building through 2025, later extending the rights until the end of the 2030 season.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Up until 2009, Anheuser-Busch was also one of the largest theme park owners/operators in the United States, with ten parks throughout the country through its entertainment division, Busch Entertainment Corporation, including its three SeaWorld locations.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The company is now known as SeaWorld Parks & Entertainment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch Companies is responsible for the production, importation and distribution of several AB InBev products, including three company-designated global brands, Budweiser, Stella Artois, and Beck's.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Other multi-country brands distributed or produced by Anheuser-Busch Companies include Leffe and Hoegaarden, while local brands produced by the company include Bass Pale Ale, Bud Light, Busch Beer, Landshark Lager, Michelob, Michelob Ultra, Natural Light, and Shock Top.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The company also produces nonalcoholic beverages, malt liquors (such as King Cobra and Hurricane), and flavored malt beverages (e.g. the Bacardi Silver family and Tequiza).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On December 22, 2015, it was announced that Anheuser-Busch would purchase Breckenridge Brewery for an undisclosed sum.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Prior to its acquisition by InBev, the company was known in the United States for its advertising presence, including a sports marketing division which created advertising material for the Super Bowl and many other sporting events.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Budweiser has sponsored horse racing events and motorsports including NASCAR, the "Miss Budweiser" racing hydroplane, and the "Budweiser King" championship top fuel dragster of Kenny Bernstein.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Since the acquisition by AB InBev, the company has significantly cut back its advertising, predicated on the belief that "changing demographics and media habits no longer require spending as much on mainstream sports events".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 2007, the company introduced a flavored 12% abv malt liquor under the name *Spykes*.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] It was sold in colorful, 2-ounce bottles.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Available flavors included mango, lime, melon and chocolate.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] It was withdrawn in the same year after criticism from alcohol industry watchdog groups that it was being marketed to underage customers, and the Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau found that the labeling of Spykes was illegal.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 2002, the Political Economy Research Institute ranked Anheuser–Busch 40th among the "Toxic 100", a list of U.S. corporations most responsible for air pollution.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The study found that Anheuser–Busch released 1,002,786 kg (2,213,657 lbs) of toxic pollutants annually into the air.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] This is mainly because large amounts of CO2 are released during the process of fermentation.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch has received numerous awards for its efforts to reduce its impact on the environment.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In addition, the Baldwinsville brewery found markets for previous "waste" materials used in the fermentation of Anheuser-Busch beers.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The Anheuser-Busch Recycling Corp. recycled more than 27 billion cans in 2006, a number far greater than what was used in its own packaging.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Similarly, Anheuser-Busch has set short-term goals to reduce energy consumption 5% and increasing use of renewable fuel from 8 to 15% by 2010.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Along with these goals, Anheuser-Busch has succeeded in cutting down its water use by 3% since 2002.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Its parent company Anheuser-Busch InBev has recently announced a commitment to secure 100% of the company's purchased electricity from renewable sources by 2025.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The brewery also operates an environmental outreach program to encourage recycling, energy conservation, and habitat preservation, as well as to prevent littering and water pollution.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] For the past 18 years Anheuser-Busch employees have participated in "Green Week", which focuses on environmental conservation education for employees and their families.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] All other Anheuser-Busch beers are brewed using water, yeast, barley malt, hops, and additional cereal grains.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch eliminates the need for isinglass finings by settling and removing particles before fermentation.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The beechwood aging process also helps to attract and remove yeast from the brew before the lagering process has ended.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] This only applies to the beers the company brews itself.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch became a pioneer for electricity-powered heavy trucks.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] It ordered hundreds of trucks from Nikola Motor, an Arizona company specialized in the development of hydrogen-fueled engines.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 2003, after numerous deaths in soccer stadiums, Brazil passed a law outlawing alcohol sales in stadiums.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] FIFA demanded that Brazil allow alcohol sales at the 2014 FIFA World Cup because Budweiser, a major World Cup sponsor is the "Official Beer of the FIFA World Cup", a role it has played since 1986.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In response, Brazil passed a law paving the way for alcohol sales in the World Cup, nicknamed the "Budweiser Bill".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Bud Light's vice president Alexander Lambrecht addressed the situation via Twitter, first saying that the slogans were meant to promote brand engagement in a "positive and lighthearted way", but that the company had "missed the mark" with their "up for whatever" slogan.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] He ended his message by saying that Bud Light would "never condone disrespectful or irresponsible behavior".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] His message was followed by a Twitter response from Lisa Weser; the former head of communications and marketing for Anheuser-Busch InBev, who also responded to the situation via Twitter.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Her response repeated Alexander Lambrecht's concluding message.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The Washington State Liquor and Cannabis Board (WSLCB) issued a $150,000 violation to Anheuser-Busch in May 2016.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Investigators determined that Anheuser-Busch entered into an illegal agreement of exclusivity with two concert venues in Seattle – the Showbox and the Showbox SoDo.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In early February 2017, Anheuser-Busch's "Budweiser – Born the Hard Way" Super Bowl commercial was released online, prompting conservative political rebuke over its depiction of the immigration of founder Adolphus Busch from Germany to St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Although the ad had been conceived eight months before its release, some perceived the ad to be a political statement in opposition to then-current president Donald Trump.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] A week before the ad's release, public controversy erupted over an executive order prohibiting entry of immigrants, refugees, and re-entry of permanent residents from seven countries into the United States.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The script for the advertisement was finalized after the November elections, when Budweiser's internal marketing team settled on the twelfth revision of the script.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Shooting for the commercial then took place in January.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The ad controversy followed after controversy in May 2016 when Trump, then a presidential candidate, was perceived by some to be hijacking Budweiser's America branding campaign for his own political purposes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On March 21, 2019, Anheuser-Busch was sued for false advertising by rival MillerCoors over a Bud Light commercial that aired during Super Bowl LIII.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The commercial claimed MillerCoors' Miller Lite and Coors Light products contain corn syrup, but the lawsuit argues that corn syrup is only used during the brewing process as a fermentation aid and neither beer contains corn syrup.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The suit alleges that Anheuser-Busch is using "false and misleading statements" to confuse health-conscious consumers into thinking the beers contain high-fructose corn syrup, which has been linked with obesity.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] An Anheuser-Busch spokesperson called the lawsuit "baseless" and said it would not deter Bud Light from "providing consumers with the transparency they demand." MillerCoors sought an injunction to prevent Bud Light from continuing the ad campaign, as well as a trial by jury and legal fees.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Anheuser-Busch prevailed in the Seventh Circuit in 2020, with the court finding that since Miller included corn syrup on the ingredients list, Anheuser-Busch was within the bounds of the Lanham Act.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On April 2, 2023, Anheuser-Busch's brand Bud Light started facing a boycott, after partnering with transgender influencer and activist Dylan Mulvaney.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Alissa Heinerscheid, the vice president of marketing behind the campaign, took a leave of absence on April 21, 2023.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] She was replaced by Budweiser Global Marketing VP Todd Allen.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Finance, on July 10, 2023, reported a recent YouGov survey's findings that Bud Light's popularity among American beer brands dropped to the 14th position.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On July 26, 2023, *The Wall Street Journal* reported that Anheuser-Busch laid off hundreds of workers at its U.S. sales offices after months of slumping sales at Bud Light.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] On February 29, 2024, CNN Business reported that Anheuser-Busch InBev experienced a significant financial hit, potentially losing up to $1.4 billion in sales.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] In 2025, Anheuser-Busch broke ties with St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis PrideFest after 30 years as the main corporate sponsor.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Louis LGBTQ and ally bars announced they would stop carrying AB products.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Adolphus Busch joined Washington University's Board of Directors in 1895, back when the school was still located on its old downtown St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Adolphus would continue to serve on the board until his death in 1913, at which point his son, August Busch Sr. took over his seat.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Though Adolphus Busch III and Gussie Busch never sat on the board, the ties between their company and the school were still strong.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] August Busch III, CEO of Anheuser-Busch from 1975 to 2002, would become a trustee of the university, a position he holds to this day.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] The Anheuser-Busch Foundation donation that gave its name to Anheuser-Busch Hall was made in honor of Fred L.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Kuhlmann, an executive officer of both the company and the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Kuhlmann, who held these positions for most of the 1980s and early 1990s, graduated from WashU's undergraduate and law programs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Though the Busch family no longer owns Anheuser-Busch, the connection between the company and the university is ongoing.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/anheuser-busch] Purnell, former CEO of Anheuser-Busch, where he worked for 36 years, is an executive in residence of the Olin Business School.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham stole 129 bases during the 1887 season.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] His career total of 742 ranks seventh all-time in the majors.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] As a player-coach for the 1909 Giants, Latham, at age 49, became the oldest MLB player to steal a base.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] After his retirement as a player, he became what is acknowledged as the first full-time base coach in baseball history.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] For years he served as a coach and manager in the minor leagues.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] After retiring from baseball, Latham traveled to Great Britain, where he organized baseball matches for soldiers during World War I and taught baseball to the British.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He later worked in baseball as a press box attendant.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham's father was a bugler in the Union Army during the American Civil War.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham became interested in baseball when soldiers returning from the battlefield brought the game of baseball with them.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] At the age of fourteen, he played with a local team from Stoneham, Massachusetts, as their catcher, fielding barehanded.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1877, he played for a team in Pittsfield, Massachusetts, as a third baseman.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham made his professional baseball debut with Springfield of the National Association in 1879.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham made his major-league debut with the Buffalo Bisons of the National League (NL) in 1880; he is considered the first man from New Hampshire to play in MLB.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He played for the Philadelphia Athletics of the Eastern Championship Association in 1881, and the Philadelphia Phillies of the League Alliance in 1882.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham returned to the major leagues with the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Louis Browns of the American Association (AA) in 1883.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham was known as an excellent base stealer in his day.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He led the AA in runs scored (152) during the 1886 season, batted .316, and stole 142 bases, plus another 12 stolen bases in the playoffs.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1887, as a member of the Browns, he stole 129 bases.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] This record is not recognized by Major League Baseball, as stolen bases were defined differently prior to 1898.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He led the league in stolen bases with 109 during the 1888 season.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1890, he jumped to the Chicago Pirates of the Players' League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He returned to the NL with the Cincinnati Reds in July 1890 to serve as a utility player and coach.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He played for Cincinnati through 1895, and was traded to the Browns after the 1895 season with Ed McFarland, Morgan Murphy, Tom Parrott and cash for Red Ehret and Heinie Peitz.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] The Browns released Latham after the 1896 season.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham then returned to the minor leagues.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He played for the Columbus Buckeyes/Senators of the Western League and Scranton Miners of the Eastern League in 1896.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He played for the Mansfield Haymakers of the Interstate League in 1897.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1898, he applied to become a NL umpire; instead, he played for the New Britain Rangers of the Connecticut State League and Hartford Cooperatives of the Atlantic League in 1898.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham returned to the major leagues with the Washington Senators in 1899.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He played for the Denver Grizzlies of the Western League in 1902.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He made a handful of cameo appearances as a player for the New York Giants of the NL in 1909, becoming the oldest man in Major League history to steal a base, at the age of 49, a record that still stands today.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham ended his career with 742 stolen bases.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham's baserunning expertise was apparently purely instinctive.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He holds the career record for errors at third base, with 822, more than 200 more than the next player on the list.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham's arm had been injured in a throwing contest with a teammate, which led to Latham making weak or half-hearted attempts to field ground balls.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham became an umpire in 1903 in the International League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1906, Latham managed the Jacksonville Jays of the Southern League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He also served as an umpire for the league and the South Atlantic League.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham was Major League Baseball's first full-time coach.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] During his playing days, he would stand on the third base line and yell insults at the other team's pitcher, attempting to distract him and give the Browns an advantage.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] One of his techniques was to scream while running up and down the third base line during the pitcher's delivery.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] The coach's box was introduced to prevent him from doing this.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] While Cy Seymour coached third base for the Giants during a game against the Philadelphia Phillies, Seymour tackled Moose McCormick as he rounded third base and headed for home plate.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] When Giants manager John McGraw asked why, Seymour made an excuse about having the sun in his eyes.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] This led McGraw, realizing the need for a full-time coach, to hire Latham for the role, the first full-time coach in MLB.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham tried to do the same things in New York as he had done years earlier in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Louis, but times had changed and screaming obscenities was not looked well upon, as baseball was being changed into more of a family-friendly game by then.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In the opinion of Giants player Fred Snodgrass, however, he was "probably the worst third base coach that ever lived".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] After the 1910 season, Latham was let go by the Giants.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In 1914, Latham coached with the Lynn Fighters of the New England League; in July 1914, he resigned from the team.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham announced his retirement from professional baseball in 1915.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He wrote for The Pittsburgh Press in 1915.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Latham lived in England during World War I, where he organized baseball for the soldiers, and taught King George V about baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He returned to the United States in 1923, and opened a delicatessen on Saint Nicholas Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] He also served as a press box attendant for the Giants at the Polo Grounds and New York Yankees at Yankee Stadium.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Known for his on-field antics, Latham was considered one of the funniest personalities in baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Nicknamed "The Freshest Man on Earth", Latham was a colorful player known for playing practical jokes, including on Browns owner Chris von der Ahe and manager Charles Comiskey.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] In one famous stunt, he lit a firecracker under third base in an effort to "wake himself up", after Comiskey had been complaining about him falling asleep on the job.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] Also he would occasionally put on a clown's nose while walking behind von der Ahe.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/arlie-latham] A practical joke Latham pulled on Cy Seymour in March 1909 caused a fight between the two at the team's hotel, prompting McGraw to discharge Seymour from the team and seek a buyer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Born in the fall of 1851 in Hille, Kingdom of Prussia, von der Ahe immigrated alone to New York City around 1870, but quickly moved to St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Louis, where he worked as a clerk in a grocery store.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Later, he bought out the store owner and expanded business by establishing a saloon in the back of the store.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Von der Ahe noticed that a number of his patrons visited the saloon after baseball games, so in 1882 he bought the bankrupt and scandal-ridden St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Louis Brown Stockings baseball franchise for $1,800 and joined the American Association baseball league.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] He named the team the Browns and hired future Chicago White Sox owner Charles Comiskey to play first base and eventually manage the team.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Von der Ahe took a very active role in the team, even though he knew almost nothing about baseball.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Other than player/manager/owner Albert Spalding, Von der Ahe was the first baseball owner with a significant public persona, the predecessor of Bill Veeck, Charlie Finley and George Steinbrenner in this regard.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] With his thick German accent ("I am der boss bresident of der Prowns!"), bushy mustache, and showmanship, he was as much of a story as his players.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] The Browns dominated the American Association, winning four straight league championships starting in 1885.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Von der Ahe's baseball, beer, and other investments made him very rich, reportedly netting $500,000 from the baseball team alone.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] He set the ticket price at 25 cents, hoping fans would spend money on beer.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] As a result, the Browns led the league in attendance and soon had to expand the ballpark.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] The term *fan* (from fanatic) is sometimes attributed to von der Ahe.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 1885, von der Ahe erected a larger-than-life statue outside of Sportsman's Park, not of any of his star players, but of himself.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] A sportswriter from Denver mockingly dubbed the statue "Von der Ahe discovers Illinois." Although eccentric, von der Ahe made a number of innovations, including operating a farm club called the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Also, tradition holds that von der Ahe was the first to sell hot dogs at the ballpark, although some historians dispute this.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Von der Ahe billed himself as the "Millionaire Sportsman".
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 1887, after a poor showing in the World Series, the ill-tempered von der Ahe threatened to withhold his players' share of the earnings.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 1891, he was also majority owner of the Cincinnati Kelly's Killers, who played for part of one season in the American Association.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 1892 the team joined the National League after the American Association folded.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Unfortunately for the Browns, they, along with three other AA refugees, were forced to place their players in a pool and give the established NL clubs first choice to sign them.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] By this time, Comiskey had lost patience with von der Ahe, and signed with the Cincinnati Reds.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Without Comiskey's eye for talent, the Browns crumbled to only their second losing record as a fully professional team, finishing 11th.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] They would never come close to contention again during von der Ahe's ownership, never finishing higher than ninth in their first seven years in the NL and even finishing last twice.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Legal problems plagued von der Ahe's ownership, especially in its later years.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In an effort to recoup his losses, in 1892 he moved to a larger ballpark, which he surrounded with an amusement park, complete with beer garden, a horse track in the outfield, a "shoot-the-shoots" water flume ride, and an artificial lake (used for ice skating in winter).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] The league, which prohibited gambling on its grounds, disapproved of the race track; so did von der Ahe's outfielders.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] With losses still piling up, von der Ahe resorted to selling off his best players, mostly to Brooklyn.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 1898, part of the ballpark burned down during an April game with Chicago; his second wife divorced him; and his bondsman kidnapped him for not paying his debts.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In a highly publicized trial connected with the fire, von der Ahe lost his baseball team.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] The Browns changed hands twice and changed their name twice, first to the Perfectos (1899) and then to the Cardinals (1900).
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] The American League team known as the St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Louis Browns from 1902 to 1953 had no connection to von der Ahe's team aside from the name, which was designed to invoke the memory of the 1885–1889 era.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Von der Ahe soon lost his other wealth as well and was reduced to tending bar in a small saloon.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Comiskey frequently sent von der Ahe money to help make ends meet.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Louis Browns played each other in a benefit game for him.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Owing to heavy lifelong alcohol consumption, he died of cirrhosis of the liver on June 5, 1913.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] He was buried in Bellefontaine Cemetery in St.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] Louis, with the statue that once stood in front of Sportsman's Park adorning his grave.
[src:chris-von-der-ahe/chris-von-der-ahe] In 2015 Von der Ahe was named to the Pre-Integration Committee ballot for the National Baseball Hall of Fame.
